Hong Kong Exchanges Net Rises 10%

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-05-11T05:17:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-11/hong-kong-exchanges-net-rises-10-.html
Hong Kong  Exchanges & Clearing
Ltd., the world’s biggest bourse by market value, said first-
quarter profit rose 10 percent as trading fees increased.  Net income advanced to HK$1.24 billion ($160 million)
from HK$1.13 billion a year earlier, the company said in a
statement today. Earnings per share climbed 11 percent to
HK$1.15, it said.  The company benefited from growth in  China , Asia’s
biggest economy, and will continue to develop financial
services to establish Hong Kong as an offshore center for the
mainland’s currency, according to the statement.  Hong Kong Exchanges plans to set up a yuan trading
support facility in September to help provide liquidity for
the yuan-denominated share market, Hong Kong Exchanges Chief
Executive Officer Charles Li said last month.  Sales rose 11 percent to HK$1.91 billion, according to
the statement. Trading fees surged 17 percent to HK$765
million, it said.  Hong Kong Exchanges has lost 0.9 percent in Hong Kong
trading this year, compared with a 1.6 percent gain in the
benchmark  Hang Seng Index .  China, the world’s second-biggest economy, grew a
more-than-estimated 9.7 percent in the first quarter and is
expected to expand 9.5 percent this year, according to
the  International Monetary Fund .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in  Tokyo  at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 